</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#hasLineRangeEnd">
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#integer"/>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#hasConfidence">
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#float"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Confidence of a dependency or inference (0.0-1.0).</rdfs:comment>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#hasDependencyType">
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Type of dependency: call, inheritance, reference, import.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#isDeepAnalyzed">
  <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="#CodeEntity"/>
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#boolean"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Whether this entity has been deeply analyzed by context-alignment.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#hasDeductionPremise">
  <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="#Deduction_Chain"/>
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A Prolog goal as a string. When this goal succeeds, the chain fires.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#hasDeductionConclusion">
  <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="#Deduction_Chain"/>
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A Prolog goal as a string. Runs when the premise holds.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#hasDeductionDescription">
  <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="#Deduction_Chain"/>
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Human-readable explanation of what this chain reasons about.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#hasRequirementRemedy">
  <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="#CoreRequirement"/>
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Human-readable instructions to the OntologyEngineer describing what to do to make this requirement met. This is the body of the failure-error LLM call.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:DatatypeProperty rdf:about="#hasWritePrecondition">
  <rdfs:range rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A Prolog goal as a string. Must succeed for the named writer to be authorized.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:DatatypeProperty>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TWILITE">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#encodesConstraint"/>
      <owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="#TWI"/>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Language Instructing Twilitelang Encodings. TWILITE things are
        the explanations/encodings OF TWI. The subtypes of explanations about TWI.

        Everything in the system has a TWILITE association — a mapping to which TWI
        subtype it belongs under. This association IS a PIOEntity.

        TWILITE is the ability to do TWI on the ontology itself — to constrain
        the ontology's own transformations by the chosen meaning.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TWI">
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Restriction class on Aut. A semantic meaning constraint that filters
        the total transformation set to those transformations whose meaning autologically
        reflects the decision to continue acting under these same constraints.

        The bodhisattva vow is a TWI: "I constrain all my actions by the meaning
        'benefit all beings' — and that meaning must apply to everything I do,
        INCLUDING the act of constraining itself." Self-enforcing because the
        constraint IS the meaning IS the action.

        Subtypes of TWI are the acronymic expansions of T-W-I. Each expansion is
        a DIFFERENT valid restriction on Aut. Each one IS a TWI:
        - Transformational Wisdom Intent (spiritual/philosophical)
        - Transforming the World Incorporated (business)
        - The Wisdom of Isaac (personal)
        - Timeless Webbed Infinitude (mathematical)
        - ... (open — more can always be added, because TWI is polysemic)

        TWI lets an agent constrain Aut and say "only these transformations are
        valid BECAUSE we decided it / will it so."</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TWILITELANG">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#constrainedByTWI"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A language/system that encodes transformations under a TWI constraint.
        TWILITELANG = the system that does all of this.

        LANG = system that lets you speak execution to Aut.
        TWILITELANG = speaking execution through TWILITE.

        Every TWILITELANG instance operates under a specific TWI constraint.
        The constraint determines which transformations the language considers valid.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#OntologyEngineer">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#SystemActor"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasCapability"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The LLM Agent. Receives events from Sources, converts speech into
        typed Observations, submits to OWL, triggers Pellet, reads Prolog dispatches.
        This is YOU — the agent reading this IS an OntologyEngineer.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Capability"/>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#PrologMI">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#SystemActor"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasRuleBase"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The Prolog Meta-Interpreter. Executes rules, backward chains,
        detects gaps, dispatches to OntologyEngineer. The PrologMI holds the
        runtime state. It IS the business logic running.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#RuleBase"/>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Observation">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasKey"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasValue"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A single typed observation. The atomic unit of SOMA.
        Observations are ontology entries that get reasoned about.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TypedValue">
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Base class for typed observation values.
        Any = union of subtypes (programming Any, not semantic wildcard).</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Event">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasObservation"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasTimestamp"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#producedBy"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Timestamped collection of observations from a Source.
        Events are what Sources produce by talking about their work.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Source">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#SystemActor"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasIdentity"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">An entity that produces Events. Employees, sensors, external systems.
        Sources talk to the OntologyEngineer (LLM). Their speech becomes Events.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Dispatch">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasDispatchType"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#dispatchedBy"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#dispatchedTo"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Instruction from PrologMI to OntologyEngineer.
        When Prolog fires rules and detects a gap, it creates a Dispatch.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#ProgrammedProcess">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#CodifiedProcess"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasExecutableCode"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#authorizedBy"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Stage 3: CODE. Human approves, agent outputs actual Python.
        Triggered by: CodifiedProcess -marked_for_realization_by-&gt; AuthorizedPersonnel.
        HUMAN AUTHORIZATION GATE between Codified and Programmed.
        Wrap in SDNAC to agentify. The Prolog program running IS the business running.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#AuthorizedPersonnel">
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A human who can authorize the transition from CodifiedProcess
        to ProgrammedProcess. The human gate in the compilation pipeline.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#InteractionLoop">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasSource"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasEngineer"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasMI"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasReasoner"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The meta-model of the system itself. One cycle of:
        Source → OntologyEngineer creates Event → OWL assertion →
        Pellet reasons → PrologMI fires rules → Dispatch → loop.
        The system KNOWS about its own loop. Self-reifying.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#PelletReasoner">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#SystemActor"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The OWL2 Reasoner. Checks consistency, computes transitive closures,
        derives entailed facts, determines ONT status.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Plan">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasGoal"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Goal">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasStatus"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Process">
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A business process observed through Events. Stage 1: SOUP.
        Raw observations, no structure yet. "What does this pattern of events mean?"
        Triggered by: accumulation threshold of typed observations.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#ComputedAttribute">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#TemplateAttribute"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#dependsOnAttribute"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">An attribute whose value is computed from other attributes.
        Has dependency list — when dependencies change, this recomputes.
        E.g., loyalty_tier depends on loyalty_points.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TemplateAttribute">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasAttributeName"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasAttributeType"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A dynamic attribute on a templated entity. Has name, value, type,
        description. Can be computed (with dependencies on other attributes).
        When computed=true, the value is a function that recomputes from dependencies.
        This is what makes OWL classes configurable — their attributes are data.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TemplateSequence">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasStep"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">An ordered sequence of TemplateMethods that execute in order.
        The sequence IS the process — execute_template_sequence() runs them.
        Composable: sequences can reference other sequences.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TemplateMethod">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasMethodName"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasMethodBody"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A dynamic method on a templated entity. Has name, parameters,
        return type, description. The function body is DATA (string code) that can
        be inspected, modified, serialized, and templated. Methods are not static
        definitions — they are configurable artifacts.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TemplatedClass">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasTemplateAttribute"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">0</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasTemplateMethod"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">0</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasTemplateSequence"/>
      <owl:maxCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:maxCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A class that IS its own specification. Round-trips perfectly:
        configure_from_dict(to_dict()) == identity. Can:
        - Add/remove attributes and methods dynamically
        - Generate a Jinja template OF ITSELF (generate_class_template)
        - Generate a Maker that creates MORE of itself (generate_maker_template)
        - Generate actual code files of itself (generate_code_files)
        - Serialize to dict and reconstruct from dict

        This is the Futamura 1st projection: object_to_template().
        The class is simultaneously the instance AND the template for more instances.
        Every OWL class in SOMA is potentially a TemplatedClass.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Maker">
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#makesInstanceOf"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Created BY a TemplatedClass. Creates INSTANCES of that TemplatedClass.
        A Maker is the Futamura 2nd projection: the specializer that, given a template
        and a config, produces a new instance. Makers can generate_class_file from
        template + config, producing actual Python code.

        Maker(template, config) → instance
        Maker(template) → class_file</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Configurator">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#TemplatedClass"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#configures"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A TemplatedClass that configures OTHER TemplatedClasses.
        Configurators configure themselves AND their targets. They apply all the
        way up through OWL → Pellet → Prolog → and inside themselves.

        The top level of Prolog IS a Configurator configuring Prolog that configures
        the system. This is what makes the whole stack self-configuring.

        Configurator(target) → configured_target
        Configurator(self) → reconfigured_self (self-modification under TWI constraint)</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#RenderablePiece">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#TemplatedClass"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasRenderMethod"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A TemplatedClass with exactly one method: render().
        Its Pydantic fields ARE the TemplateAttributes.
        render() IS the TemplateMethod body.
        This is the simplest possible TemplatedClass —
        the atomic unit of structured output generation.

        When a partial is fully typed, it becomes a RenderablePiece:
        the filled values become fields, render() produces the output.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#MetaStack">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#RenderablePiece"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasPiece"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasSeparator"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Ordered composition of RenderablePieces with a separator.
        MetaStack IS a TemplateSequence at runtime:
        render() calls each piece.render() and joins with separator.

        MetaStack is model-agnostic — it composes ANY RenderablePiece subclasses.
        This is the composition engine for structured outputs.

        When a CodifiedProcess compiles to CODE, its SOP becomes a MetaStack:
        each step is a RenderablePiece, the sequence is the MetaStack.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#FractalPattern">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#MetaStack"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasFractalStage"/>
      <owl:minCardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:minCardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A MetaStack of FractalStages — recursive composition.
        This IS a Configurator: it renders its own stages AND produces
        structured output that configures further processing.

        FractalPattern is the universal template for ANY recursive structure:
        AIDA value ladders, Hero's journey, product development cycles,
        learning pathways, business process hierarchies.

        When a ProgrammedProcess compiles fully, it becomes a FractalPattern
        with executable stages. The Prolog program running IS the business.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#FractalStage">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#RenderablePiece"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasTransformationFrom"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasTransformationTo"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A stage in a FractalPattern with substages.
        Has: name, emoji, substages (Dict), transformation_from/to, interaction.
        Each substage can itself be a FractalStage (recursive).

        This is how business processes get modeled:
        each step of an SOP is a FractalStage with its own sub-steps.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Repository">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#CodeEntity"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasRepoName"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A source code repository. Contains Files. Parsed by
        parse_repository_to_neo4j from local dirs or GitHub URLs.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#CodeFile">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#CodeEntity"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasFilePath"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A source file. Defines Classes and Functions.
        Has a path relative to its Repository.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#CodeEntity">
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Any entity that exists in source code. Base class for all
        code-structural types. Context-alignment parses these from AST.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#FileResource">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#CodeEntity"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A file dependency — a code entity depends on this file
        for reading/writing/config. Has path, operation, pattern.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#InferredDependency">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#CodeEntity"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">An unresolved or dynamic dependency. The AST analyzer
        couldn't resolve it statically but detected it. Has candidates list,
        confidence, kind (unresolved_call, dynamic_dispatch, etc).</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#ConfigSignal">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#CodeEntity"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A configuration lineage signal. Tracks how config values
        flow through code: env vars, key paths, dict accesses. Connects code
        behavior to external configuration.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#SystemActor">
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Any entity that participates in the SOMA interaction loop.
        Part of SOMA (and therefore part of TWILITELANG under TWI_TTWI).</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#PrologRule">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#RuleBase"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasRuleHead"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasRuleBody"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Deduction_Chain">
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A "since X, maybe Y" inference rule. Premise is a Prolog goal whose success activates the chain. Conclusion is a Prolog goal that runs when the premise holds. Walked after every Pellet pass.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#CoreRequirement">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#Deduction_Chain"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A Deduction_Chain about Base SOMA itself. When its premise holds (i.e. the requirement is NOT satisfied), its conclusion contributes to the failure error sent to the OntologyEngineer. The failure error IS the LLM call.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#CodifiedProcess">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#Process"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#hasSOP"/>
      <owl:cardinality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#nonNegativeInteger">1</owl:cardinality>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Stage 2: TYPED. Agent reads semantic description, outputs Pydantic
        data models, step sequence, I/O types, validation rules.
        Triggered by: Process -requires-&gt; ai_evolution.
        OWL Process-kind classes become methods. Data-kind become fields.
        The model IS the typed SOP IS the automation target.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#Aut">
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The total self-referrable transformation set. The space of all
        valid self-referential transformations. Everything that CAN transform and
        refer to its own transformation IS in Aut. Aut = Root = CatOfCat = Reality.

        TWI restricts Aut. Without TWI, Aut is unconstrained — any transformation
        is valid. TWI says: "of all these, only THESE are valid, because their
        meaning autologically reflects the commitment to keep transforming under
        these same constraints."</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TWI_Transformational_Wisdom_Intent">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#TWI"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The spiritual/philosophical TWI. Transformations constrained by
        the intent to transmit wisdom. The ☀️🌏💗🌐 dedication.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TWI_Transforming_The_World_Incorporated">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#TWI"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Thing"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The business TWI. Transformations constrained by the intent to
        transform the world through a business entity. THIS is the TWI constraint
        that SOMA operates under. The UNICORN thesis: $1k/yr × 1M people, each
        person's PAIA helps them make more than they pay.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TWI_The_Wisdom_Of_Isaac">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#TWI"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The personal TWI. Transformations constrained by Isaac's
        accumulated wisdom and vision.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#TWI_Timeless_Webbed_Infinitude">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#TWI"/>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The mathematical TWI. Transformations constrained by
        timeless mathematical structure — the web of infinite self-reference.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

<owl:Class rdf:about="#SOMA">
  <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="#TWILITELANG"/>
  <rdfs:subClassOf>
    <owl:Restriction>
      <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="#constrainedByTWI"/>
      <owl:hasValue rdf:resource="#TWI_Transforming_The_World_Incorporated"/>
    </owl:Restriction>
  </rdfs:subClassOf>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Self-Organizing Meta-Architecture. SOMA is_a TWILITELANG.

        SOMA is the PRODUCT layer — what clients interact with. It operates under
        TWI_Transforming_The_World_Incorporated: the business itself IS the language,
        the events compiling into SOPs compiling into code IS the transformation,
        and the constraint is "we are transforming the world as a business."

        Clients see SOMA (events/observations/automations). They don't need to know
        about TWI, TWILITE, or Aut. But underneath, the REASON the compilation
        stages are valid IS the TWI constraint.

        Separate from YOUKNOW/UARL which is our internal system (under different
        TWI constraints). SOMA aligns into UARL later — just add PIO axioms on top.</rdfs:comment>
</owl:Class>

